SIMPLE: hight
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hight
<hw>Hight</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A variant of
<er>Height</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hight</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hight
<hw>Hight</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Hight</conjf>, <conjf>Hot</conjf>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hight</conjf>,
<conjf>Hote</conjf> (<?/), <conjf>Hoten</conjf> (<?/). See
<er>Hote</er>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>heiten</ets>,
<ets>highten</ets>, <ets>haten</ets>, <ets>hoten</ets>; also
<ets>hight</ets>, <ets>hatte</ets>, <ets>hette</ets>, is called, was
called, AS. <ets>h⟦amac⟧tan</ets> to call, name, be called, to command,
promise; also <ets>h⟦amac⟧tte</ets> is called, was called; akin to G.
<ets>heissen</ets> to call, be called, bid, Goth. <ets>haitan</ets> to
call, in the passive, to be called.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be called
or named.</def> <mark>[Archaic & Poetic.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In the form <xex>hight</xex>, it is used in a passive
sense as a present, meaning <xex>is called</xex> or <xex>named</xex>,
also as a preterite, <xex>was called</xex> or <xex>named</xex>. This
form has also been used as a past participle. See
<er>Hote</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The great poet of Italy,⟦br⟧
That <qex>highte</qex> Dante.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bright was her hue, and Geraldine she <qex>hight</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Surrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Entered then into the church the Reverend Teacher.⟦br⟧
Father he <qex>hight</qex>, and he was, in the parish.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Childe Harold was he <qex>hight</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To command; to direct; to impel.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But the sad steel seized not where it was <qex>hight</qex>⟦br⟧
Upon the child, but somewhat short did fall.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To commit; to intrust.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet charge of them was to a porter <qex>hight</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To promise.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had hold his day, as he had <qex>hight</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hightener</ent>⟦br⟧
